  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the difference between human milk and cow milk?",
  "response": "Human milk and cow milk differ significantly in their composition, nutritional content, and suitability for infants. Here are the main differences:\n\n### Composition:\n**Human Milk:**\n- **Protein:** Human milk contains lower protein content (about 0.8-1.2 grams per 100 ml) compared to cow milk. The proteins in human milk are primarily whey (about 60-80%) and casein (20-40%), which are easily digestible and beneficial to the infant.\n- **Fat:** Human milk has higher fat content (about 3.5-4.5 grams per 100 ml) and contains a higher concentration of essential fatty acids and long-chain polyunsaturated fats, important for brain development.\n- **Carbohydrates:** Human milk has higher lactose content (about 7 grams per 100 ml), which serves as a primary source of energy and aids in calcium absorption.\n- **Vitamins & Minerals:** Human milk is rich in vitamins and minerals, but infants may need vitamin D and iron supplements.\n\n**Cow Milk:**\n- **Protein:** Cow milk has higher protein content (about 3.2-3.5 grams per 100 ml) and contains mostly casein (about 80%) and less whey (20%), which can be harder to digest for infants.\n- **Fat:** Cow milk contains about 3.3-4 grams of fat per 100 ml, but the fat composition is different and less suited to human infants.\n- **Carbohydrates:** Cow milk has lower lactose content (about 4.8 grams per 100 ml).\n- **Vitamins & Minerals:** Cow milk is rich in calcium but lacks adequate vitamin C. It also has lower levels of essential fatty acids and higher amounts of sodium and potassium compared to human milk.\n\n### Suitability for Infants:\n**Human Milk:**\n- Specifically designed to meet the nutritional needs of human infants.\n- Contains antibodies and immunological factors that help protect infants from infections and diseases.\n- Easier to digest for infants.\n- Breastfeeding fosters mother-child bonding.\n\n**Cow Milk:**\n- Not suitable for infants under 12 months because its composition can be hard on infant kidneys and digestive systems.\n- Can be an ingredient in infant formula after modification to be closer to human milk.\n- Typically introduced after 1 year of age when the toddler's digestive system is more mature.\n\n### Health Implications:\n**Human Milk:**\n- Promotes healthy growth and development.\n- Lowers risks of infections, allergies, and chronic conditions.\n- Provides long-term benefits in cognitive development and immune health.\n\n**Cow Milk:**\n- Not recommended for infants under 12 months because it can cause digestive problems, kidney strain, and increase the risk of iron-deficiency anemia.\n- After 1 year, it can be a good source of calcium and vitamin D, important for bone development.\n\nIn summary, human milk is specifically tailored to meet the nutritional and developmental needs of human infants, promoting health and growth. Cow milk, while beneficial for older children and adults, is not suitable for infants and requires modification when used in infant formula.",
